data.post: So the city doesn't want to spend money on two stop signs at an intersection near a school to prevent car accidents, until one does happen then they will consider it.  I hope that two cars don't try to avoid each other and in turn hit an elementary school kid.  He gave me some real BS excuses to why people should already know how this very uncommon intersection works and who should yield to who.  He said putting in stop signs gives other people on the non-stop sign side the excuse to speed up... Even though the other street wouldn't even see the sign because of how this intersection is laid out.  He said if there is a crash then the one at fault would be the one in trouble.  Then I stumped him with "Who's at fault, if there are no signs?".  "The city only places stop signs at intersections that get 2000+ cars a day"... I can only think of a few places that might get that many cars a day and they all have signal lights anyways.  Well the next accident I see I will be sure to document it and put the photos on this guys desk.

data.post: Not sure if people got the message on their cellphone or home phones earlier about a missing girl but I heard it and look up the description.  These kinds of things you think to yourself that you'll never actually find them or what are the chances.  My chances were high today I guess.  After I looked up the info on www.amissingchild.com I decided to start my work out and go for a couple mile run. Half way through I see a young girl fitting the description so I thought for a bit what to do since I did not bring my phone this time. Luckily a women was coming from her house and I asked to use hers. told the cops whats up and where she was heading, I followed her all discretely until I saw a cop a couple blocks over and flagged him down.  She was not happy to see him, she was definitely a run away and he said she had done it before. Well that's my good deed for the year. Missed my appointment at school because of it too.

Well it looks like my new car is on the way.  2014 Hyundai Accent SE Hatchback, black exterior, gray mix interior, all the bells and whistles.  Got a sweet deal and an even better deal today.  Since the one they were originally trying to get (same thing but black interior) sold they got this new one that just got off the truck yesterday (meaning even newer than the other) and comes with even more extras.  Since we already made the deal and locked it the price of what I will pay, I'm not being charged anymore for this more expensive car. Even though I didn't get my black interior I got a sweet deal overall. Should be picking it up Wednesday morning. Thank you to my friend Mike for the online help in car buying, I feel like a got a good win with this purchase.

Pics coming soon...

P.S. I know I did good and the sales lady I worked said I did good because she showed me the sales person board in the office and pointed out that she made no extra money off this deal while other people made around 180 from other car buyers that didn't do as much research.  Luckily with most dealers she said she gets a percentage from the manufacturer and state for selling a car so I don't feel bad.

external_context.source: "My Humps" is a song performed by American recording group The Black Eyed Peas. The song was written and produced by group member will.i.am for their fourth studio album Monkey Business (2005). It was released as the band's third single from the album on September 20, 2005, due in part to the strength of downloads preceding the release. Musically, "My Humps" is a hip hop and dance song that is structured as a duet between will.i.am and Fergie. The song sparked controversy because of its title and lyrics, which center on a woman who uses her breasts and buttocks to accomplish her goals.

external_context.source: "Breezeblocks" is a song by British indie rock band alt-J from their debut studio album An Awesome Wave (2012). The song was released on 18 May 2012 as the album's second single. The song was written by Joe Newman, Gus Unger-Hamilton, Gwilym Sainsbury, Thom Green, Murad Merali and produced by Charlie Andrew. It reached the top ten in the UK Indie and US Alternative charts, and was voted into third place in Australian radio station Triple J's Hottest 100 of 2012, behind "Thrift Shop" and "Little Talks".

external_context.name: Jump Around
external_context.source: "Jump Around" is a hit song by American hip hop group House of Pain, produced by DJ Muggs of Cypress Hill, who has also covered the song. It became a hit in 1992, reaching number 3 in the group's native United States. A 1993 re-release of the song in the United Kingdom, where the initial release had been a minor hit, peaked at number 8. On VH1's 100 Greatest Songs of the 90s, "Jump Around" was featured at position 24. It was number 66 on VH1's 100 Greatest Songs of Hip Hop. The song is popular among dancehall DJs and is widely regarded in the United Kingdom as a club classic. Blender's 500 Greatest Songs Since You Were Born listed it at number 325.

People may think I have mental issues but I'll never regret it. Started running for fun and fitness the summer of 13' and was never interested in racing when I could just run for free. At the end of last year I re began my training after my motorcycle accident and surgery. I never thought I would run or workout out to my best again. Since October I have pushed my limits and become even stronger and faster. In January I participated in my first over 8 mile race (Cascade half marathon) and found out I run a lot faster than I expected. That got me hooked on going the distance. Not long after, my best running inspiration/competition decided to help coach me on the side and on her time to make me a better all around runner. Coach Kate has put up with my runner n00b questions to help me begin to get past being a baby runner (someday ;) ) . Couldn't have done it without her. Also the enormous support and advice I receive from my favorite running husband/wife duo, John and Susan Gallagher. These two support so many people in this community through the work they do in and out of the store. I recommend that everyone go there whether you are a runner/walker or just love a comfy work shoe, come join the running club. 

Today was the first marathon attempt I have taken and did exactly what I wanted to do, complete it and try to do it in under 4 hours. From this point on I will make myself better until I reach my goal to BQ and get to Boston within the next 5 years. After mile 18 I was starting to see "The Wall" and a couple miles later there it was. I pushed through the best I could and then was very surprised coming to the finish line when I heard my name yelled not thinking I would even know anyone around. The parents Johnny and Eileen said they would probably not make it but sacrificed some sleep to support me anyways (you can see dad running next to me on the other side of the fence). A great surprise. Unfortunately I had a "tight" recovery window at the beach and did have to long to spend there at the finish line. Walked a steep hill (ugh) to the car then raced to the hotel before checkout which I squeezed them out for 12:30, for the chilling ice bath (it helped). After that the long drive home for some R&R. 

Newport Marathon, 2017- Complete! 
3:51:22 finish time. 

#marathon #first #running #newportoregon #goals #PR

Also awesome to see Matt Fitzgerald again since the Eugene marathon. He killed it of course, well done. Also was able to get the parents out there for some fun. Next time they have to run the whole thing.

Silver Falls 7-miler in the morning. Luckily we get an extra hour of sleep tomorrow.

Forecast is looking good for the falls right now.

No service there so be back later.

Today I did my first ever âtrailâ race/run (never run on anything more off pave than bark chips). The Silver Falls 7-miler was around the 10 falls and a bit of extra. Went into it thinking I would maybe get a pace of 8:45m/mile since Iâve never run a trail and do not have the proper shoes (which made me nervous about slipping, only rolled my ankle once... itâs a bit sore now). I started in the front and thought Iâd just see how it went from there. Well it turns out Iâm pretty good on or off the paved paths. For the first 5-ish miles I kept up with a locally know star Tonya and kept a 7:15ish pace. After that around the lower south falls before the stairs I thought Iâd see what I could do. I didnât really go faster since it was all up hill but I left everyone behind and passed 3 more people. The up slope and stairs are tough. I canât even imagine what the other people are feeling doing the marathon and 50k. Felt good to finish 6th overall and first in my division with a time of 55:33. I am extra tired. Good job to all my friends running the longer races and being volunteers too! 
#beatyesterday

data.post: Well the refs won this game. Lol good try yall.

Well today was the end of the first week of 5k #training. I wasnt supposed to #race but I wanted a #baseline for Eola No Hills 5k. I went out with the leaders as usual, but slowed down because I was way ahead of my wanted end time. At this race last year I earned my #PR of 18:27 and was so happy to break the 19min point. This year is the year I wanted to brake the 18min point. Somehow I did it today, just barely. Looks like I have to set some higher #goals for #Eola. Thank you everyone for the support and congrats today. Also congrats to everyone else who ran it and made their goals in the race you ran today.  #corvallisrunning #fallfestivalrun Heart Of The Valley Runners Willamette Valley Road Runners Gallagher Fitness Resources

Edit: also looks like I got a new mile PR. 5:19.2
Just please dont lose. #gohawks

life_event.title: Marionette doll with Mario
life_event.description: After a couple years of thinking I went for it and got my buddy Mario to do his magic in creating this amazing realistic marionette doll. I came to him with a basic wooded doll idea and days later he found me this amazingly creepy piece of art. Not affraid to say this was by far the most painful tattoo and life experience I have had to date. So many times I wanted to quit but I toughed it out the best I could for 6 hours.... If you are looking for an amazing artist I know the 3 best in salem!

title: J Hanson wrote on Susan Glatter Gallagher's timeline.

data.post: About to do a Zwift trainer ride for ALS charity with 6000+ other people. I hope my laptop does explode.

Zwift had a charity ride today and for each person that completed the one hour group ride they would donate $1 to an ALS charity up to $10,000. There were 10,080 people this morning. That was a lot of people to ride with at once. The game does load everyone on my screen though or it would explode but it was cool to see so many riders. Had a 45min warm up ride before giving me 38miles total for this morning.

Todayâs adventure took us first to fork in the road. This was Alisonâs surprise for me. Haha. Then we went to Mt. Pisgah down in Springfield, Oregon. Ran around the mountain for a couple hours getting 9miles and 2k ft climbed for some great views. Weather was perfect. Some muddy trails and a little bit of off roading to make a steep shortcut to the top.

media.title: Hiking in Sweet Home
media.description: Todayâs #adventure took us #south again to the @sweethomeoregon area. First stop was #McDowell #Creek County #Park #Majestic #falls and #Royal Terrace falls. Next was the #ghost town of Hwy 20 east of sweet home. Kind of funny and interesting. After that we were off to another set of #hikes. Just across the #bridge and down the road it was Cascadia campgrounds. Soda Falls and Soda Spring Trail. We we got there and a guy said there was some sort of animal on animal attack at the end where the cave was... Well it was not a cave and not an attack. More like someone brushed or sheered their husky. But we did find so extra nice water #views past the end of the trail. A nice dinner stop at #Barsidious Brewing in Lebanon, damn good fryâs and tots.

data.post: Today we did a bit of #climbing back to some places I couldnât get to before. We #hiked up to Dome Rock and got some great #views. From the we went a long way down to Tumble #Lake found a little pocket #gopher on the way down. Found a #waterfall and a nice place to sit and #snack while looking into the #valley. From there it was a huge amount of #climbing out to get to the top of Sardine #Mountain. We took the no #trail route. Not easy. More great views and some nice #cloud cover. #Sliding down the mountain completed our #journey. Overall just about 10 miles and around 3500ft climbed. Iâm #tired time for a beer #pnwonderland #pnw #hiking #hike #hikes #mountains #flowers #critters #scenery  @ Opal Creek Wilderness

data.post: Our little rascal found his way back to us early this morning. Last night we were out till past midnight looking. Seen him around but he wouldnât get close enough to realize it was us. Army crawled with caution towards her then tackled her with excitement once he knew. This was him at 5:30am coming home and greeting me at the bed then he quickly remembered where he sleeps and acted like all was normal again. What a little turd. Glad heâs back though. Time to start some real training soon. Oh and time to purchase a GPS collar.

life_event.title: Networking+ (N10-007) certified
life_event.description: Super stressful last few days. At the beginning of February I left work to start a Network Development Engineering program to get my N+, Linux+ certifications. Along with training in AWS and Python. For the last month I have been cramming everything N+ related into my little brain and today was my exam. Halfway through the test I had doubts and really thought I was in trouble. Thankfully the outcome was better than I could have asked. Passed this exam by plenty and I can now finally take a weekend to relax. I'm excited to continue this course to get more certificates and education to further my career.

Hello family and friends! I wanted to get on here and let everyone know that I have not told already that I recently acquired a new job which has me relocating to the north Seattle area. Since January I have participated in a Network Engineering Development program through a company in Bellevue, WA called TLG Learning. With their assistance I was able to get a couple great CompTIA certifications and other useful skills for the field. I had thought since the beginning that they were going to help me get a job in this new field and they did not disappoint. In fact they offered me a position within their own company (I guess I did alright through the program). So my expected last day in Oregon (for now) is May 28th. I just signed the lease for my new place up in the north Seattle area today and will be finishing out my last two weeks of work here and then preparing to move for the next week. I will miss everyone very much but I know I will be back often for running events and definitely for family get togethers. This is no a goodbye but a see you soon.
Happy birthday! Happy Mothers Day too! Double gifts right? Enjoy!!

Finally getting out to explore Seattle a little bit. Went on a history tour at pioneer square. Itâs crazy how much this city has become over only two generations. A little blurb from the tour- Pioneer Square is ground zero when it comes to Seattleâs history. Pioneer Square has seen it all: Broadsides from battleships, mob lynchings, gunfights right out of a Clint Eastwood movie, Indian attacks right out of a John Wayne movie. And letâs not forget âHere Come the Bridesââtrue story. Famous speakers, congressional suicides, conflagration, a secret underground city, the worldâs first base jumper and much more.
To you and dad. Lol
Bought my first in person Seahawks game tickets ever last night for me and family. Going to be an awesome day. Hopefully itâs a tie so nobody gets hurt. Darell hide the frying pan from Krissi.

Doing a little exploring tonight. The simply named Fin Art in Seattle's Magnuson Park is a larger-than-life work of recycled art that turns a grassy field into teeming ocean.Â 

Located just off the shore of Lake Washington, the large, black shapes that comprise the public art piece resemble nothing so much as a pod of killer whales, peeking their fins above the waterline. Upon closer inspection, what seemed to be fins are revealed to be painted metal monoliths planted in the ground at irregular angles and intervals creating a sense of live motion. The pieces are in fact decommissioned submarine wings that each weigh 10,000 pounds. This use of military ordinance to create public art which celebrates life is far more affecting than the simple title of Fin Art would suggest.
